# Minimum Operations To Make Array XOR k

## Solution

### Intuition

* Flipping one bit in any array element also flips that same bit in the XOR of the whole array.
* So the only thing that matters is which bit positions are different between the current XOR and the target value.
* Every different bit needs exactly one flip, so the answer is just the number of differing bits.

### Approach

* Find the XOR of all elements to get the current XOR of the array.
* Compare this value with the target to identify the bit positions that do not match.
* Count how many such bit positions exist.
* Return that count as the minimum number of operations.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
minOperations(nums, k) {
    /* Store the XOR of all array elements so we know the current final XOR */
    xorValue = 0

    /* Traverse the array and combine every element into one XOR value */
    for i = 0 to nums.size() - 1 {

        /* Update the running XOR with the current element */
        xorValue = xorValue ^ nums[i]
    }

    /* Convert the current XOR into a mask of bit positions that must change */
    xorValue = xorValue ^ k

    /* Store the minimum number of flips needed */
    count = 0

    /* Each set bit in the mask represents one required operation */
    while xorValue != 0 {

        /* Count the current differing bit */
        count = count + 1

        /* Remove the lowest set bit to continue counting efficiently */
        xorValue = xorValue & (xorValue - 1)
    }

    /* Return the minimum number of operations */
    return count
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int minOperations(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int xorValue = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            xorValue ^= nums[i];
        }

        xorValue ^= k;

        int count = 0;
        while (xorValue != 0) {
            count++;
            xorValue = xorValue & (xorValue - 1);
        }

        return count;
    }
};

/*
int main() {
    int n, k;
    cin >> n >> k;

    vector<int> nums(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    solution sol;
    int result = sol.minOperations(nums, k);
    cout << result << endl;

    return 0;
}
*/
```

```python
class solution:
    def minOperations(self, nums, k):
        xorValue = 0

        for i in range(len(nums)):
            xorValue ^= nums[i]

        xorValue ^= k

        count = 0
        while xorValue != 0:
            count += 1
            xorValue = xorValue & (xorValue - 1)

        return count


'''
if __name__ == "__main__":
    n, k = map(int, input().split())
    nums = list(map(int, input().split()))

    sol = solution()
    result = sol.minOperations(nums, k)
    print(result)
'''
```

```java
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public static int minOperations(List<Integer> nums, int k) {
        int xorValue = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            xorValue ^= nums.get(i);
        }

        xorValue ^= k;

        int count = 0;
        while (xorValue != 0) {
            count++;
            xorValue = xorValue & (xorValue - 1);
        }

        return count;
    }
}

