### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n log n)`**

  * Inserts all `n` elements into a `set`, and each insertion takes `O(log n)`.
  * Copying elements from the set back to the array takes `O(n)`, which is dominated by insertion time.
  * Therefore, overall time complexity is `O(n log n)`.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * Uses an extra `set` to store unique elements.
  * In the worst case (all elements distinct), the set stores all `n` elements, so extra space is linear.

## Optimal Approach(Two pointer approach)

### Intuition

* Because the array is already sorted, duplicates appear next to each other.
* So we keep one pointer at the last unique element and another pointer to scan forward.
* Whenever the scanning pointer finds a new value (different from the last kept one), we place it next in the unique section.
* This builds the deduplicated array in-place at the beginning, and its length becomes the count of kept unique values.

### Approach

- Set the index variable `i` to 0 as an initial step.

- Traverse the array starting from the second element using the variable `j`.

- If the current element (`j`) differs from the previous one (`i`), replace the element at index `i+1` with the current element and increment the value of `i`.

