### Complexity Analysis

**Time Complexity** will be **`O(n)`**

- If the array is already sorted, the algorithm will make a single pass through the array to check if any swaps are needed.

- In each pass, it will find the array is sorted, and the algorithm terminates early.

**Worst Case time complexity:**

- Bubble sort uses two nested loops. The outer loop runs from `i = n-1` down to `i = 1`, effectively iterating through each element.

   - In the first iteration, the inner loop runs `n-1` times.

   - In the second iteration, the inner loop runs `n-2` times.

   - This pattern continues until the last iteration, where the inner loop runs only 1 time.

```pseudocode
Time Complexity = 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + (n-1)
                = ((n-1) * (n-1+1))/2
                = (n * (n-1)) / 2
                = (n^2)/2 - n/2
                = O((n^2)/2 - n/2)
                = O(n^2)
```
- Worst and Average Case Time Complexity of Bubble sort is **`O(n^2)`**, where `n` is the size of array

**Best Case Time Complexity:**

**Example**

When the given array is already sorted

```pseudocode
arr[] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50} -> best case
```

**Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

*  *Extra variables used:* loop counters (`i`, `j`) and a few helpers (`swapped`, `temp`) → all constant-sized.
* *No additional arrays/lists:* sorting is done *in-place* by swapping within the same array.
* *Space does not depend on `n`:* memory usage stays constant for any input size.

* *Space Complexity:* **O(1)** (constant auxiliary space)

# Sorting in Decreasing Order 

## Bubble Sort in Descending Order

### Intuition

* We need the largest values to move toward the beginning of the array.
* A simple way to do that is to compare neighboring elements and swap them whenever the left one is smaller than the right one.
* After each full pass, one more element reaches its correct position, but this method is slower for large arrays because it uses many repeated comparisons.

### Approach

* Start from the beginning of the array and compare neighboring elements.
* Swap them whenever they are not in decreasing order.
* Repeat this process for multiple passes until the whole array becomes sorted.
* Print the updated array after sorting is complete.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
bubbleSort(arr, n) {
    /* Repeat passes so that each pass places one element in its correct position */
    for i = 0 to n - 2 {

        /* Compare adjacent elements in the unsorted part of the array */
        for j = 0 to n - i - 2 {

            /* Swap when the left element is smaller, because we want decreasing order */
            if arr[j] < arr[j + 1] {

                /* Exchange the two elements to move the larger one left */
                temp = arr[j]
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1]
                arr[j + 1] = temp
            }
        }
    }

    /* Sorting is complete, so return */
    return
}
```

</CodeBlock>

