# Lower Bound

## Solution

### Intuition

Since the array is already sorted, we don’t need to scan all elements one by one.
We can use binary search thinking to quickly locate the first position where `arr[i] >= x`.

The key observation is:

* If `arr[mid] >= x`, then mid could be the answer, but there might be an even smaller valid index on the left side. So we store mid in `ans` and move `high` left.
* If `arr[mid] < x`, then mid can’t be the lower bound, and neither can anything to the left of it. So we move `low` right.

We keep doing this until `low > high`.
If we never find any `arr[mid] >= x`, `ans` stays as `n`, meaning all elements are smaller than `x`, so the lower bound is after the last element.

### Approach

- Initialize variables for the low and high indices and set an initial answer variable (`ans`) to the size of the array. 

- Update the answer when the mid-element is greater than or equal to the target value.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vTZA-N150HtlzV8MBCGoTwfZUVtjqWHy4vb_zjqRA1vuTGzUJhwwi70zG78pLT2Yy8WjwSPO0csxhj4/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">
```plaintext
lowerBound(arr, n, x)
{
    /* low and high are the current search range */
    low = 0
    high = n - 1

    /* Default answer is n (means: no element >= x found) */
    ans = n

    /* Binary search to find first index with value >= x */
    while low <= high {
        /* Find middle index of current range */
        mid = (low + high) / 2

        if arr[mid] >= x {
            /* mid can be a valid lower bound, store it */
            ans = mid

            /* Try to find an even smaller index on the left side */
            high = mid - 1
        } else {
            /* arr[mid] < x, so lower bound must be on the right side */
            low = mid + 1
        }
    }

    /* Return the lower bound index */
    return ans
}
```
</CodeBlock>

