# Upper Bound

## Solution

### Intuition

Because the array is sorted, all values `<= x` will appear before all values `> x`.
So the upper bound is simply the first position where the value becomes strictly greater than `x`.

While doing binary search:

* If `arr[mid] > x`, then mid can be the upper bound, but there might be an even earlier index on the left that is also `> x`.
  So we store mid in `ans` and move `high` left.

* If `arr[mid] <= x`, then mid is not an upper bound, and nothing on the left of mid can be an upper bound either (since they’ll be `<= arr[mid] <= x`).
  So we move `low` right.

At the end, `ans` holds the smallest index with value > x.
If no such value exists, `ans` remains `n`, meaning the upper bound is past the last element.

### Approach

- Initialize variables for the low and high indices and set an initial answer variable (`ans`) to the size of the array. 

- Update the answer when the mid-element is greater than target value.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
