# Binary to Decimal Conversion

## Solution

### Intuition

* In a binary number, each position represents a power of two, so every digit contributes based on where it appears.
* Starting from the right side is natural because the rightmost digit always represents the smallest value, and each step to the left doubles that value.
* This works because binary follows place value rules just like decimal, but with powers of two instead of powers of ten.

### Approach

* Start from the last digit of the binary string and move toward the first digit.
* Keep a running value that represents the current power of two for that position.
* Whenever the current digit is one, add the current power value to the answer.
* Double the current power after processing each digit and continue until all digits are checked.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
binary_to_decimal(str) {

    /* Initialize the final decimal value as zero */
    ans = 0

    /* Start with the smallest power of two for the rightmost bit */
    prod = 1

    /* Store the size of the binary string for traversal */
    n = str.size()

    /* Traverse the string from right to left to process each bit by position */
    for i = n - 1 to 0 {

        /* Add the current positional value only when the bit is one */
        if str[i] == '1' {

            /* This bit contributes its current power of two to the answer */
            ans = ans + prod
        }

        /* Move to the next higher power of two for the next position */
        prod = prod * 2
    }

    /* Return the computed decimal value */
    return ans
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int binary_to_decimal(string str) {
        int ans = 0;
        int n = str.size();
        int prod = 1;

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (str[i] == '1') {
                ans += prod;
            }
            prod = prod * 2;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

