### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n log n)`**

  * The array is traversed once to update frequencies in the map, and each update takes `O(log n)` in the worst case.
  * The stored entries are scanned once more to collect the two numbers with odd frequency.
  * The dominant term is `O(n log n)` because ordered map updates cost more than the final linear scan.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The map can store frequencies for up to all distinct elements in the array, so extra memory grows with the input size.
  * Apart from the map and the two-element answer list, only constant extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(n)`.

## Solution 2: XOR Partitioning

### Intuition

* Every number that appears an even number of times cancels itself when XOR is applied repeatedly.
* After XORing the whole array, only the XOR of the two odd occurring numbers remains.
* A set bit in that result tells us that the two required numbers differ at that position, so we can split the array into two groups and recover both numbers separately.

### Approach

* XOR all elements of the array to get the XOR of the two odd occurring numbers.
* Find the rightmost set bit in that XOR result.
* Divide the array into two groups based on whether that bit is set or not, and XOR each group separately.
* The two final XOR values are the required numbers, so return them in decreasing order.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
oddOccurence(arr) {
    /* Store the array size for traversal */
    n = arr.size()

    /* Start with the first element so the full XOR can be built */
    xorr = arr[0]

    /* This will store the rightmost set bit of the XOR result */
    setBit = 0

    /* These two values will become the odd occurring numbers */
    x = 0
    y = 0

    /* Keep the final answer in decreasing order */
    ans = {}

    /* XOR all elements so even occurrences cancel out */
    for i = 1 to n - 1 {
        xorr = xorr ^ arr[i]
    }

    /* Isolate the rightmost set bit where the two numbers differ */
    setBit = xorr & ~(xorr - 1)

    /* Split numbers into two groups using that set bit */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* XOR numbers whose chosen bit is set */
        if arr[i] & setBit {
            x = x ^ arr[i]
        }

        /* XOR numbers whose chosen bit is not set */
        else {
            y = y ^ arr[i]
        }
    }

    /* Store the larger number first */
    if x > y {
        ans.push_back(x)
        ans.push_back(y)
    }

    /* Store the numbers in decreasing order when y is larger */
    else {
        ans.push_back(y)
        ans.push_back(x)
    }

    /* Return the answer when both numbers are collected */
    if ans.size() == 2 {
        return ans
    }

    /* Safety return if no valid pair is found */
    return {-1, -1}
}
```

</CodeBlock>

