### Complexity Analysis

**Time Complexity:**

-  **Outer Loop (i)**

   - The outer loop runs from `i = 0` to `n-2` (inclusive)

   - This means it executes `n-1` times

- **Inner Loop (j)**

   - The inner loop runs from `j = i` to `n-1` (inclusive)

   - it iterates `n-i` times in each iteration of the outer loop

```pseudocode
Time Complexity = n + (n-1) + (n-2) + ...... + 2
                = n + (n-1) + (n-2) + ...... + 2 + 1  ----> Adding 1 for approximation (which doesn't affect the time complexity)
                = n(n + 1)/2
                = ((n^2)/2) + (n/2) ----> Ignoring constants and lower powers
                = O(n^2)
```
- *Time Complexity* will be **O(n^2)**

**Space Complexity:**

* *Extra variables used:* `min_index`, `i`, `j`, `temp` → all are constant-sized variables.
* *No extra data structures:* The algorithm sorts the array in-place (no additional arrays/lists).
* *Space does not grow with `n`:* Memory usage remains the same regardless of input size.
* *Space Complexity* will be **O(1)** (constant auxiliary space)

# Sorting Array in Decreasing Order

## Selection Sort for Descending Order

### Intuition

* We need the largest values to appear first, so at every position we should place the biggest remaining element there.
* The natural idea is to scan the unsorted part of the array, find the maximum element, and move it to the current position.
* This works because once the largest remaining element is placed, that position is final and never needs to be touched again.

### Approach

* Start from the first position of the array and treat it as the place where the next largest element should go.
* Scan the remaining unsorted part of the array to find the maximum element.
* Swap that maximum element with the current position.
* Repeat this for every position until the whole array becomes sorted in decreasing order.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
selectionSort(arr, n) {

    /* Go through each position and place the correct largest remaining element there */
    for i = 0 to n - 2 {

        /* Assume the current position holds the largest value for this pass */
        maxIndex = i

        /* Search the remaining part of the array for a larger element */
        for j = i + 1 to n - 1 {

            /* Update the maximum position when a larger element is found */
            if arr[j] > arr[maxIndex] {

                /* Store the new position of the largest element seen so far */
                maxIndex = j
            }
        }

        /* Swap the current element with the largest element found in this pass */
        swap arr[i], arr[maxIndex]
    }

    /* Sorting is complete, so return */
    return

}
```

</CodeBlock>

