### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * We traverse the array once and update the frequency of each element during that pass.
  * Each frequency table update takes constant time on average, so the full scan costs linear time.
  * The dominant term is `O(n)` because every element is processed exactly once.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The frequency table may store an entry for every distinct element in the array.
  * A few extra variables are also used to track the current answer and best frequency.
  * Total space used is `O(n)`.

# Half Pair Check

## Solution 1: Nested Pair Checking

### Intuition

* The most direct idea is to compare every possible pair and check whether one number is exactly half of the other.
* This works because trying all pairs guarantees that no valid answer is missed.
* The drawback is that the same comparisons are repeated many times, so it becomes slow for large arrays.

### Approach

* Check every element against every other element in the array.
* For each pair of different positions, first make sure the larger candidate can actually have an integer half.
* Compare the smaller candidate with half of the larger candidate.
* Return true as soon as a valid pair is found, otherwise return false after all pairs are checked.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
hasHalf(arr, n) {

    /* Check every possible first position in the array */
    for p = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Compare the current element with every possible second position */
        for q = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* Ensure both positions are different and the larger candidate has a valid integer half */
            if p != q and arr[q] % 2 == 0 and arr[p] == arr[q] / 2 {

                /* A valid half pair is found, so return true immediately */
                return true
            }
        }
    }

    /* No valid pair exists in the array, so return false */
    return false
}
```

</CodeBlock>

