## Solution 2: Hash Set Lookup

### Intuition

* Instead of checking all pairs, we can remember numbers we have already seen while scanning the array once.
* For each number, a valid pair exists if its half was seen earlier, or if its double was seen earlier.
* This avoids repeated comparisons and makes the solution much faster in practice.

### Approach

* Create a set to store numbers that have already been processed.
* While scanning the array, check whether the current number can pair with a previously seen half.
* Also check whether the current number can pair with a previously seen double.
* If either check succeeds, return true immediately.
* Otherwise add the current number to the set and continue until the array ends.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
hasHalf(arr, n) {

    /* Store previously seen numbers for fast lookup */
    S = {}

    /* Process each number one by one */
    for p = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Check whether the current number can match with its half already seen */
        if arr[p] % 2 == 0 and S.has(arr[p] / 2) {

            /* A valid half pair is found, so return true */
            return true
        }

        /* Check whether the current number can match with its double already seen */
        if S.has(2 * arr[p]) {

            /* A valid half pair is found, so return true */
            return true
        }

        /* Save the current number for future checks */
        S.insert(arr[p])
    }

    /* No valid pair exists after scanning the whole array */
    return false
}
```

</CodeBlock>

