# Pattern Word Matching with Bijection

## Solution

### Intuition

* A valid match must stay consistent in both directions, so one letter cannot point to two different words and one word cannot point to two different letters.
* A simple way to verify this is to remember when each letter and each word was last seen.
* If the current letter and current word do not share the same last seen position, the pattern is broken.

### Approach

* Read the words of the sentence in order and match them with the pattern characters one by one.
* Keep one lookup table for pattern characters and another for words.
* For each position, compare the previous position stored for the current character and the current word.
* If the two previous positions differ, return false because the mapping is inconsistent.
* Otherwise, store the current position in both tables and continue until the scan ends.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
wordPattern(pattern, s) {

    /* Store the last matched position for each pattern character and each word */
    p2i = empty map
    w2i = empty map

    /* Start from the first position and remember the pattern length */
    i = 0
    n = pattern.size()

    /* Read the sentence one word at a time */
    in = stream from s

    /* Process every word in order */
    while in has next word {

        /* Take the next word from the sentence */
        word = next word from in

        /* If words are more than pattern characters, matching is impossible */
        if i == n {
            return false
        }

        /* If both sides were last seen at different positions, the mapping breaks */
        if p2i[pattern[i]] != w2i[word] {
            return false
        }

        /* Mark this character and word as seen at the same position */
        p2i[pattern[i]] = i + 1
        w2i[word] = i + 1

        /* Move to the next pattern position */
        i = i + 1
    }

    /* The number of processed words must exactly match the pattern length */
    return i == n
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    bool wordPattern(string pattern, string s) {
        unordered_map<char, int> p2i;
        unordered_map<string, int> w2i;

        istringstream in(s);
        string word;
        int i = 0, n = pattern.size();

        for (; in >> word; i++) {
            if (i == n || p2i[pattern[i]] != w2i[word]) {
                return false;
            }

            p2i[pattern[i]] = i + 1;
            w2i[word] = i + 1;
        }

        return i == n;
    }
};

