### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n + k + m * f)`**

    * Finding the largest element in the first array takes `O(n)` time, where `n` is the size of the first array.

    * Filling the count array by scanning the first array takes `O(n)` time.

    * For each element in the second array, we add it to the result as many times as it appears in the first array, which takes `O(m * f)` time, where `m` is the size of the second array and `f` is the average count of elements.

    * Scanning the count array and adding remaining elements takes `O(k)` time, where `k` is the range of numbers (the largest element in the first array).

    * Overall, the time complexity is `O(n + k + m * f)`. When `k` is small compared to `n`, this simplifies to approximately `O(n + m * f)`.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n + k)`**

    * The count array uses `O(k)` space, where `k` is the range of numbers.

    * The result array uses `O(n)` space to store all elements from the first array.

    * Overall, the space used is `O(n + k)`.

# Minimum Number of Balls in the Box

## Solution 1: Brute Froce Solution

### Intuition

* Each value tells us the size of a color group, because a ball reporting `x` means its color appears in a group of size `x + 1`.
* For any fixed set of reports, the minimum balls contributed by one value depends only on how many times that value appears.
* Since we may ignore at most one report, the most direct idea is to try every possible ignored index.
* After removing one report, recompute the minimum valid total for the remaining reports and keep the smallest answer.

### Approach

* Write a helper function that skips one chosen index and counts the frequency of every reported value in the remaining array.
* For each distinct reported value, compute the minimum number of balls needed by rounding its frequency up to the nearest multiple of that group size.
* First compute the answer when no report is ignored.
* Then try ignoring each index one by one and recompute the total.
* Return the minimum total over all these cases.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
computeMin(counts, idx) {

    /* Store how many times each reported value appears after exclusion */
    map mp

    /* Initialize the total balls needed for this scenario */
    ans = 0

    /* Build the frequency map while skipping the ignored index */
    for i = 0 to counts.size() - 1 {

        /* Ignore the chosen report so this scenario uses only the remaining reports */
        if i == idx {
            continue
        }

        /* Count how many balls reported the same value */
        mp[counts[i]]++
    }

    /* Process every distinct reported value independently */
    for it : mp {

        /* The current reported value decides the group size */
        curr = it.first

        /* The number of balls that reported this value */
        cnt = it.second

        /* Round up to the minimum full groups needed for this value */
        res = ceil((double)cnt / (curr + 1)) * (curr + 1)

        /* Add this group's contribution to the total */
        ans = ans + res
    }

    /* Return the minimum balls needed for this exclusion choice */
    return ans
}

minimumBalls(counts) {

    /* Start with the case where no report is ignored */
    ans = computeMin(counts, -1)

    /* Test every index as the one ignored report */
    for i = 0 to counts.size() - 1 {

        /* Recompute the answer after excluding this index */
        res = computeMin(counts, i)

        /* Keep the smallest total seen so far */
        ans = min(ans, res)
    }

    /* Return the minimum total over all valid scenarios */
    return ans
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int computeMin(vector<int>& counts, int idx) {
        int n = counts.size();
        unordered_map<int, int> mp;
        int ans = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (i == idx) {
                continue;
            }
            mp[counts[i]]++;
        }

        for (auto& it : mp) {
            int curr = it.first;
            int cnt = it.second;
            int res = ceil((double)cnt / (curr + 1)) * (curr + 1);
            ans += res;
        }

        return ans;
    }

    int minimumBalls(vector<int>& counts) {
        int n = counts.size();
        int ans = computeMin(counts, -1);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int res = computeMin(counts, i);
            ans = min(ans, res);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

