# Sum of Factorials of Digits

## Recursive Digit Extraction

### Intuition

* Process the number one digit at a time from right to left.
* For each digit, compute its factorial and add it to the answer.
* After using the last digit, remove it and recursively solve the same problem for the remaining number.
* This works naturally because every recursive call handles one smaller part of the original number.

### Approach

* Create a helper function to calculate the factorial of a single digit recursively.
* In the main recursive function, extract the last digit using modulo.
* Add the factorial of that digit to the result of the recursive call on the remaining digits.
* Stop the recursion when the number becomes `0`.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
factorial(x) {
    /* Base case: factorial of 0 and 1 is 1, so recursion stops here */
    if (x == 0 || x == 1) {
        /* Return the known factorial value for the smallest inputs */
        return 1
    }

    /* Recursive step: multiply the current number by factorial of the previous number */
    return x * factorial(x - 1)
}

sumOfFactorialsOfDigits(n) {
    /* Base case: when no digits are left, there is nothing more to add */
    if (n == 0) {
        /* Return 0 because all digits have already been processed */
        return 0
    }

    /* Extract the current last digit so its factorial can be added */
    digit = n % 10

    /* Remove the last digit to continue recursion on the remaining number */
    remaining = n / 10

    /* Add factorial of the current digit to the answer from the remaining digits */
    return factorial(digit) + sumOfFactorialsOfDigits(remaining)
}
```

</CodeBlock>

