# Factorial Sequence Generator

## Solution

### Intuition

* The factorial sequence has a natural recursive pattern: to build the sequence up to `n`, we first need the sequence up to **`n - 1`**.
* Once we already know all factorials from `1!` to `(n-1)!`, the next value is easy to get by multiplying the last factorial by `n`.
* So the problem can be reduced into a smaller version of itself, and then extended by adding one new value.
* The recursion keeps shrinking the problem until it reaches the first factorial, which is already known directly.
* As the recursive calls return, each level appends the next factorial to the list, gradually constructing the full sequence.

### Approach

* We define a recursive function that generates the factorial sequence up to `n`.
* The base case occurs when `n == 1`, where the sequence is simply `[1]`.
* For the recursive case, we first compute the factorial sequence up to `n - 1`.
* Then we append the next factorial value by multiplying `n` with the last value already present in the sequence.
* In this way, the full factorial sequence is built step by step as the recursion unwinds.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```
factorialSequence(n) {
    /* Base case */
    if n == 1 {
        return [1]
    }
    /* Recursive case */
    result = factorialSequence(n - 1)

    /* Append next factorial */
    result.append(n * result[-1])

    return result
}
```

</CodeBlock>

