  * Apart from that, only a few constant extra variables are used.
  * Total space used is `O(n)`.

## Solution 2: Stable Backward Shift

### Intuition

* We want zeroes at the front, but the non-zero elements must stay in the same order.
* If we shift non-zero elements from the back, we can place them safely without disturbing values that still need to be processed.
* After moving all non-zero elements to the right places, the remaining front part can simply be filled with zeroes.

### Approach

* Count how many zeroes are present in the array.
* Traverse the array from right to left and place each non-zero element at its correct final position.
* Keep moving the write position left whenever a non-zero element is placed.
* Fill the first part of the array with zeroes.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
moveZerosToFront(arr, n) {

    /* Count zeroes so we know how much space must be reserved at the front */
    zeroCount = 0

    /* Traverse the whole array to count all zero values */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* A zero contributes to the front block */
        if arr[i] == 0 {

            /* Increase the number of zeroes found */
            zeroCount = zeroCount + 1
        }
    }

    /* Start writing from the end of the array */
    writeIndex = n - 1

    /* Traverse from right to left to preserve the order of non-zero elements */
    for i = n - 1 to 0 {

        /* Only non-zero elements need to be shifted */
        if arr[i] != 0 {

            /* Place the current non-zero element at the current write position */
            arr[writeIndex] = arr[i]

            /* Move the write position one step left */
            writeIndex = writeIndex - 1
        }
    }

    /* Fill the reserved front block with zeroes */
    for i = 0 to zeroCount - 1 {

        /* These positions must contain zero in the final array */
        arr[i] = 0
    }

    /* Return the modified array */
    return arr
}
```

</CodeBlock>

