### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The array is scanned once from left to right, which takes `O(n)`.
  * Each map lookup and insertion takes `O(1)` on average, so the total map work across all elements is `O(n)`.
  * The dominant term is `O(n)` because every element is processed once with constant average extra work.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The map can store the first occurrence of many different running totals, which may grow up to `n + 1` entries.
  * The remaining variables use only constant extra memory.
  * Total space used is `O(n)`.

# Shortest Subarray with Sum k

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* A simple way to solve this is to try every possible starting position and keep extending the subarray to the right.
* While extending, we keep a running sum, so we do not need to recompute the full sum from scratch every time.
* This always finds the correct answer, but it becomes slow because there can be many subarrays to check.

### Approach

* Start from each position in the array one by one.
* Extend the subarray to the right while maintaining its running sum.
* Whenever the running sum becomes equal to the target, update the shortest length found so far.
* After checking all starting positions, return the shortest length, or return failure if no valid subarray exists.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
/* Check every possible starting position and extend the subarray to the right */
shortestSubarrayWithSumK(arr, n, k) {

    /* Store the best answer found so far */
    minLength = inf

    /* Try every index as the starting point of the subarray */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Reset the running sum for the new starting point */
        sum = 0

        /* Extend the subarray one element at a time */
        for j = i to n - 1 {

            /* Add the current element to the running sum */
            sum += arr[j]

            /* Check whether the current subarray matches the target */
            if sum == k {

                /* Update the best answer using the current subarray length */
                minLength = min(minLength, j - i + 1)
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return failure if no valid subarray was found */
    if minLength == inf {
        return -1
    }

    /* Return the shortest valid subarray length */
    return minLength
}
```

</CodeBlock>

