### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n²)`**

  * For each index, the algorithm scans the left part of the array and the right part of the array to compute both sums.
  * These repeated scans can together take linear work for every index in the worst case.
  * The dominant term is `O(n²)` because each candidate position triggers additional traversal of the array.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * Only a few variables are used to store the current sums and loop counters.
  * No extra array or auxiliary data structure is created.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

## Solution 2: Prefix Sum and Suffix Sum Arrays

### Intuition

* Recomputing sums for every position is wasteful.
* Instead, we can precompute cumulative sums from the left and from the right.
* Once those arrays are built, the left sum and right sum for any index can be obtained immediately.
* This avoids repeated summation and makes the overall process linear.

### Approach

* Build a prefix sum array where each position stores the total from the start up to that index.
* Build a suffix sum array where each position stores the total from that index to the end.
* For each index, use the previous prefix value as the left sum and the next suffix value as the right sum.
* Return the first index where both values are equal.
* If no such index exists, return -1.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
findStablePosition(arr) {
    /* Store the size of the array */
    n = size of arr

    /* Store prefix sums */
    prefixSum = array of size n
    /* Store suffix sums */
    suffixSum = array of size n

    /* Build the prefix sum array */
    prefixSum[0] = arr[0]
    for (i from 1 to n - 1) {
        prefixSum[i] = prefixSum[i - 1] + arr[i]
    }

    /* Build the suffix sum array */
    suffixSum[n - 1] = arr[n - 1]
    for (i from n - 2 down to 0) {
        suffixSum[i] = suffixSum[i + 1] + arr[i]
    }

    /* Check every index for balance */
    for (i from 0 to n - 1) {
        /* Sum before index i */
        leftSum = (i == 0) ? 0 : prefixSum[i - 1]
        /* Sum after index i */
        rightSum = (i == n - 1) ? 0 : suffixSum[i + 1]

        /* Return i if both sums are equal */
        if (leftSum equals rightSum) {
            return i
        }
    }

    /* No stable position exists */
    return -1
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int findStablePosition(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();

        vector<int> prefixSum(n), suffixSum(n);

        prefixSum[0] = arr[0];
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            prefixSum[i] = prefixSum[i - 1] + arr[i];
        }

        suffixSum[n - 1] = arr[n - 1];
        for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            suffixSum[i] = suffixSum[i + 1] + arr[i];
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int leftSum = (i == 0) ? 0 : prefixSum[i - 1];
            int rightSum = (i == n - 1) ? 0 : suffixSum[i + 1];

            if (leftSum == rightSum) {
                return i;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};

