# Subarray Product Below K

## Solution 1: Nested Subarray Expansion

### Intuition

* The most direct idea is to start from every position and keep extending the subarray to the right.
* Since all numbers are positive, once the product becomes at least the limit, adding more elements will only make it larger, so we can stop early for that start.
* This method is easy to understand and always works, but it can still take a lot of time in the worst case.

### Approach

* Start a subarray from each index of the array.
* Keep multiplying elements as you extend that subarray to the right.
* Count the subarray whenever its product stays smaller than the given limit.
* Stop extending the current subarray as soon as the product becomes too large, then move to the next starting index.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
subarrayProductBelowK(arr, k) {
    /* Store the total number of valid subarrays */
    count = 0

    /* Try every index as the starting point of a subarray */
    for i = 0 to arr.size() - 1 {

        /* Reset the running product for the new starting point */
        product = 1

        /* Extend the current subarray one element at a time */
        for j = i to arr.size() - 1 {

            /* Include the current element in the running product */
            product = product * arr[j]

            /* Count this subarray if its product stays below the limit */
            if product < k {

                /* Add the current valid subarray to the answer */
                count = count + 1
            }

            /* Stop because any longer subarray will only have a larger product */
            if product >= k {

                /* No need to extend this starting point further */
                break
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the total number of valid subarrays found */
    return count
}
```

</CodeBlock>

