### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n^2)`**

  * The outer loop starts a new subarray from every index of the array.
  * For each starting point, the inner loop may still scan many ending positions in the worst case.
  * The dominant term is `O(n^2)` because many start and end pairs can be examined.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * The method uses only a few extra variables for the running product and total count.
  * Only constant extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

## Solution 2: Sliding Window with Running Product

### Intuition

* Because all elements are positive, increasing the right side of a window increases the product, and moving the left side forward decreases it.
* This makes it possible to maintain a valid window whose product stays smaller than the limit.
* Once the window becomes valid, every subarray ending at the current position and starting inside that window is also valid, which lets us count many subarrays at once.

### Approach

* Return zero immediately when the limit is zero or one, because no positive product can be smaller than one.
* Keep a window with a running product and expand it one element at a time from the right.
* Whenever the product becomes too large, move the left side forward and remove those elements from the product.
* After making the window valid, add the number of valid subarrays that end at the current position.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
subarrayProductBelowK(arr, k) {
    /* No positive subarray product can be smaller than 1 */
    if k <= 1 {

        /* Return 0 because no valid subarray can exist */
        return 0
    }

    /* Store the running product of the current window */
    product = 1

    /* Store the total number of valid subarrays */
    count = 0

    /* Mark the left boundary of the current window */
    left = 0

    /* Expand the window by moving the right boundary */
    for right = 0 to arr.size() - 1 {

        /* Include the current element in the window product */
        product = product * arr[right]

        /* Shrink the window until the product becomes valid again */
        while product >= k {

            /* Remove the leftmost element from the running product */
            product = product / arr[left]

            /* Move the left boundary forward */
            left = left + 1
        }

        /* Count all valid subarrays that end at the current position */
        count = count + (right - left + 1)
    }

    /* Return the total number of valid subarrays found */
    return count
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    long long subarrayProductBelowK(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        if (k <= 1) {
            return 0;
        }

        long long product = 1;
        long long count = 0;
        int left = 0;

        for (int right = 0; right < (int)arr.size(); right++) {
            product *= arr[right];
            while (product >= k) {
                product /= arr[left];
                left++;
            }
            count += right - left + 1;
        }
        return count;
    }
};

