### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The right boundary moves from left to right across the array only once.
  * The left boundary also moves forward at most once for each element while shrinking the window.
  * The dominant term is `O(n)` because each element is processed at most twice.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * The method keeps only a running product, two pointers, and the final count.
  * Only constant extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

# Continuous Subarray Sum

## Solution 1: Sliding Window Approach

### Intuition

* A simple idea is to look at every subarray ending at the current position and check whether its sum is divisible by the given number.
* We can keep a running total and then remove elements from the left side one by one to test shorter subarrays ending at the same place.
* This works, but many overlapping subarrays get checked again and again, so it becomes slow for large inputs.

### Approach

* Start from the second element and keep updating the running sum from the beginning up to the current position.
* Immediately return true if two consecutive zeroes appear, because their sum is zero and the length is at least two.
* If the current running sum is divisible by the given number, return true.
* Otherwise, keep removing elements from the left side of that running sum to test smaller subarrays ending at the current position.
* If none of these sums is divisible by the given number, continue to the next position.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
/* Check whether there exists a valid subarray of length at least two */
checkSubarraySum(arr, m) {

    /* Start the running sum with the first element */
    Sum = arr[0]

    /* Try every ending position from the second element onward */
    for i = 1 to arr.size() - 1 {

        /* Two consecutive zeroes form a valid subarray */
        if arr[i - 1] == 0 && arr[i] == 0 {

            /* A valid subarray is found */
            return true
        }

        /* Extend the running sum to include the current element */
        Sum = Sum + arr[i]

        /* If the prefix itself is divisible, it is a valid subarray */
        if Sum % m == 0 {

            /* A valid subarray is found */
            return true
        }

        /* Start removing elements from the left to test smaller suffixes */
        j = 0

        /* Begin with the full running sum for this ending position */
        tempSum = Sum

        /* Keep shrinking while the remaining subarray still has length at least two */
        while (i - j) > 1 && tempSum >= m {

            /* Remove the leftmost element of the current candidate subarray */
            tempSum = tempSum - arr[j]

            /* Move the left boundary one step forward */
            j = j + 1

            /* Check whether the reduced sum is divisible */
            if tempSum % m == 0 {

                /* A valid subarray is found */
                return true
            }
        }
    }

    /* No valid subarray exists */
    return false
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    bool checkSubarraySum(vector<int>& arr, int m) {
        int Sum = arr[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            if (arr[i - 1] == 0 && arr[i] == 0) {
                return true;
            }

            Sum += arr[i];

            if (Sum % m == 0) {
                return true;
            }

            int j = 0;
            int tempSum = Sum;

            while ((i - j) > 1 && tempSum >= m) {
                tempSum -= arr[j];
                j++;

                if (tempSum % m == 0) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
};

