### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n^2)`**

  * The outer loop checks each ending index of the subarray once.
  * For every ending index, the inner loop may remove many earlier elements and test many candidate sums.
  * The dominant term is `O(n^2)` because, in the worst case, a large number of subarrays are examined.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * Only a few extra variables are used to store running sums and indices.
  * No additional data structure grows with the input size.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

## Solution 2: Prefix Sum Modulo with Hash Map

### Intuition

* If two prefix sums leave the same remainder when divided by the given number, the sum between them must be divisible by that number.
* So instead of checking every subarray directly, we only need to track which remainders have already appeared.
* The first time a remainder appears is the most useful, because it gives the longest possible distance and helps us ensure the subarray length is at least two.

### Approach

* Keep a running remainder of the prefix sum instead of storing the full sum.
* Store the first position where each remainder appears.
* Pretend remainder zero appears before the array starts so subarrays beginning at the first element are handled naturally.
* When the same remainder appears again, check whether the distance between the two positions is at least two.
* If such a distance exists, return true; otherwise continue until the array ends.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
/* Check whether there exists a valid subarray using prefix remainders */
checkSubarraySum(arr, m) {

    /* Store the running prefix remainder */
    prefixMod = 0

    /* Store the first index where each remainder appears */
    modSeen = {}

    /* Pretend remainder zero appears before the array starts */
    modSeen[0] = -1

    /* Process each element from left to right */
    for i = 0 to arr.size() - 1 {

        /* Update the running remainder after including the current element */
        prefixMod = (prefixMod + arr[i]) % m

        /* If this remainder was seen before, a divisible subarray may exist */
        if modSeen.find(prefixMod) != modSeen.end() {

            /* Ensure the subarray length is at least two */
            if i - modSeen[prefixMod] > 1 {

                /* A valid subarray is found */
                return true
            }
        }
        else {

            /* Store the first occurrence of this remainder */
            modSeen[prefixMod] = i
        }
    }

    /* No valid subarray exists */
    return false
}
```

</CodeBlock>

