# Count Set Bits in an Integer

## Solution 1: Check Every Bit One by One

### Intuition

* The binary representation of a number contains bits that are either `0` or `1`.
* A set bit means the bit is `1`.
* We can repeatedly check the last bit of the number using `N & 1`.
* After checking it, we right shift the number so the next bit becomes the last bit.

### Approach

* Initialize a counter `count` as `0`.
* While `N` is not `0`:

  * check whether the last bit is set using `N & 1`
  * if it is set, increment `count`
  * right shift `N` by one bit
* Return `count`.

### Pseudocode

```customtext
countSetBits(N) {
    count = 0  /* Store the total number of set bits */

    while N != 0 {
        /* Check whether the last bit of N is 1 */
        if (N & 1) == 1 {
            /* Increase count when the current bit is set */
            count = count + 1
        }

        /* Right shift N by 1 to check the next bit */
        N = N >> 1
    }

    return count  /* Return the total number of set bits */
}
```

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int countSetBits(int N) {
        int count = 0;

        while (N != 0) {
            if ((N & 1) == 1) {
                count++;
            }
            N = N >> 1;
        }

        return count;
    }
};

