# String Concatenation Length

## Summing Individual String Lengths

### Intuition

* We only need the length of the final joined string, not the string itself.
* So instead of actually joining all strings, we can just add the length of each string one by one.
* This works because the total length after concatenation is exactly the sum of all individual lengths.

### Approach

* Start with a total length of zero.
* Go through each string in the array.
* Add the length of the current string to the total.
* Return the final total length.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
lengthAfterConcat(arr, n) {

    /* Store the final length of the concatenated string */
    totalLength = 0

    /* Visit every string once to add its contribution */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Add the current string length to the running total */
        totalLength = totalLength + length of arr[i]
    }

    /* Return the total length after processing all strings */
    return totalLength

}
```

</CodeBlock>

