# Reversing Array Sections

## Solution

### Intuition

* We only need to reverse the part of the array from index `left` to index `right`.

* The first element of this section should swap with the last element, the second with the second last, and so on.

* So we can use two pointers, one starting from `left` and one starting from `right`.

* After one swap, the same work remains for the smaller inner section, which makes recursion a natural fit.

### Approach

* Use a recursive function that works on the current indices `left` and `right`.

* If `left` becomes greater than or equal to `right`, stop because the required section is already reversed.

* Otherwise, swap `arr[left]` and `arr[right]`.

* Then recursively call the same function for the inner subarray from `left + 1` to `right - 1`.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
reverseArraySection(arr, left, right) {
    /* If pointers meet or cross, the section is fully reversed */
    if (left >= right) {
        return
    }

    /* Swap the outer elements of the current section */
    temp = arr[left]
    arr[left] = arr[right]
    arr[right] = temp

    /* Recursively reverse the remaining inner section */
    reverseArraySection(arr, left + 1, right - 1)
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    void reverseArraySection(vector<int>& arr, int left, int right) {
        if (left >= right) {
            return;
        }

        swap(arr[left], arr[right]);
        reverseArraySection(arr, left + 1, right - 1);
    }
};

