  * The recursion stack grows as the function moves inward.
  * The maximum depth is proportional to the size of the selected section.
  * So the extra space used is linear in the size of the reversed subarray.

# Recursive Mirror Image Array

## Solution

### Intuition

* Since the array length is even, being a mirror image means the first half should exactly match the reverse of the second half.

* That is the same as checking whether the first element equals the last element, the second equals the second last, and so on.

* So we can use recursion with two pointers, one from the left end and one from the right end.

* If every mirrored pair matches until the pointers meet or cross, the array is a mirror image.

### Approach

* Use a recursive helper function with two indices: `left` and `right`.

* If `left` becomes greater than or equal to `right`, all required mirrored pairs have already matched, so return `true`.

* If `arr[left]` is not equal to `arr[right]`, return `false` immediately.

* Otherwise, recursively check the inner part by moving `left` forward and `right` backward.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
helperFunc(arr, left, right) {
    /* If pointers meet or cross, all mirrored pairs are valid */
    if (left >= right) {
        return true
    }

    /* If current mirrored elements do not match, array is not a mirror image */
    if (arr[left] != arr[right]) {
        return false
    }

    /* Recursively check the next inner mirrored pair */
    return helperFunc(arr, left + 1, right - 1)
}

isMirrorImage(arr, n) {
    /* Check the full array using two pointer recursion */
    return helperFunc(arr, 0, n - 1)
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
