# Minimum Bit Flips To Convert an Array

## XOR with Set Bit Counting

### Intuition

* For each pair of numbers, we only care about the bit positions where they are different.
* XOR helps here because it gives `1` exactly at the positions where the two numbers do not match.
* So the answer for each pair becomes the number of set bits in the XOR result. This is correct because each different bit needs exactly one flip.

### Approach

* Go through both arrays together and compare the numbers at the same index.
* For each pair, take their XOR to find all bit positions that differ.
* Count how many set bits are present in that XOR value using the trick that removes the lowest set bit in one step.
* Store that count in the result array and return the final array after all pairs are processed.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
helperFunction(start, goal, ans) {
    /* Find the bit positions where the two numbers differ */
    Xor = start ^ goal

    /* Start the flip counter from zero */
    count = 0

    /* Keep removing one set bit at a time until no differing bit remains */
    while Xor != 0 {

        /* One set bit means one required flip */
        count = count + 1

        /* Remove the lowest set bit to continue counting efficiently */
        Xor = Xor & (Xor - 1)
    }

    /* Store the answer for this pair */
    ans.push_back(count)
}

minBitFlips(n, arr1, arr2) {
    /* Create an empty array to store the result for each index */
    ans = {}

    /* Process every pair of corresponding elements */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Count flips needed for the current pair and save it */
        helperFunction(arr1[i], arr2[i], ans)
    }

    /* Return the final array of answers */
    return ans
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    void helperFunction(int start, int goal, vector<int> &ans) {
        int Xor = start ^ goal;
        int count = 0;

        while (Xor != 0) {
            count += 1;
            Xor = Xor & (Xor - 1);
        }

        ans.push_back(count);
    }

    vector<int> minBitFlips(int n, vector<int> &arr1, vector<int> &arr2) {
        vector<int> ans;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            helperFunction(arr1[i], arr2[i], ans);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

