# Two Sum

## Solution 1: Brute Force Solution

### Intuition

* The simplest idea is to check every possible pair of elements and see whether their sum matches the target.
* Since every pair is examined once, this method is guaranteed to find a valid answer if one exists.
* It is easy to understand, but it becomes slow for large arrays because the number of pairs grows quickly.

### Approach

* Start from the first element and compare it with every element that comes after it.
* For each pair, calculate their sum and check whether it matches the target.
* Return the two indices as soon as a valid pair is found.
* If no pair gives the target sum, return a failure result.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
twoSum(arr, k) {
    /* Store the size of the array */
    n = arr.size()

    /* Check every possible first index */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Check every possible second index after the first */
        for j = i + 1 to n - 1 {

            /* Return the pair if the target sum is found */
            if arr[i] + arr[j] == k {
                return {i, j}
            }
        }
    }

    /* No valid pair was found */
    return {-1, -1}
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        int n = arr.size();

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                if (arr[i] + arr[j] == k) {
                    return {i, j};
                }
            }
        }

        return {-1, -1};
    }
};

