# Two Sum II

## Two-Pointer Search on a Sorted Array

### Intuition

* Since the array is sorted, the smallest values are on the left and the largest values are on the right.
* If the current sum is too large, moving the right side left makes the sum smaller. If the current sum is too small, moving the left side right makes the sum larger.
* This lets us find the only valid pair in one pass without using extra space.

### Approach

* Start with one pointer at the beginning of the array and another at the end.
* Find the sum of the values at these two positions.
* If the sum equals the target, return their 1-based positions.
* If the sum is greater than the target, move the right pointer left; otherwise, move the left pointer right.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
twoSum(arr, target) {

    /* Start with one pointer at the beginning and one at the end of the array */
    left = 0
    right = arr.size() - 1

    /* Keep checking pairs until the two pointers meet */
    while left < right {

        /* Compute the sum of the current pair */
        total = arr[left] + arr[right]

        /* If the current pair matches the target, return 1-based indices */
        if total == target {

            /* Valid answer found */
            return {left + 1, right + 1}
        }

        /* If the sum is too large, move the right pointer left */
        if total > target {
            right = right - 1
        }

        /* If the sum is too small, move the left pointer right */
        else {
            left = left + 1
        }
    }

    /* No valid pair exists */
    return {-1, -1}
}
```

</CodeBlock>

