### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n^2 * log m)`**

  * The outer loop fixes one element, and the inner loop scans the remaining elements, giving `O(n^2)`.
  * Each valid triplet is inserted into the set, which costs `O(log m)`.
  * The dominant term is `O(n^2 * log m)`.

* **Space Complexity: `O(m + n)`**

  * The set stores unique triplets, which takes `O(m)`.
  * For each fixed index, the hash set `seen` can store up to `O(n)` elements.
  * So the total auxiliary space is `O(m + n)`.

# Four Sum

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* The most direct idea is to try every possible group of four elements and check whether their sum matches the target.
* This works because every valid quadruplet will eventually be examined.
* The main difficulty is avoiding duplicate quadruplets when the same values appear in different positions.
* Sorting each valid quadruplet before storing it in a set keeps only unique answers, but this method is very slow.

### Approach

* Check every possible choice of four distinct elements using four nested loops.
* For each group of four elements, calculate their total sum.
* If the sum matches the target, sort those four values and store them in a set.
* Convert all unique quadruplets from the set into the final answer and return it.

### Pseudocode

```customtext
fourSum(arr, target) {
    /* Store the size of the array and all unique quadruplets */
    n = arr.size()
    st = empty set

    /* Try every possible first element */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Try every possible second element after the first */
        for j = i + 1 to n - 1 {

            /* Try every possible third element after the second */
            for k = j + 1 to n - 1 {

                /* Try every possible fourth element after the third */
                for l = k + 1 to n - 1 {

                    /* Check whether the current quadruplet forms the target sum */
                    sum = arr[i] + arr[j] + arr[k] + arr[l]

                    if sum == target {

                        /* Sort the quadruplet so the same values always look identical */
                        temp = {arr[i], arr[j], arr[k], arr[l]}
                        sort(temp)

                        /* Store only unique quadruplets */
                        insert temp into st
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    /* Convert the set into the final list of answers */
    ans = elements of st

    /* Return all unique quadruplets */
    return ans
}
```

