# Count Subarrays with Target Sum

## Solution 1: Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* The most direct idea is to generate every possible subarray and calculate its sum.
* If the sum of a chosen subarray matches the target, we count it.
* This always gives the correct answer, but it is very slow because the same elements are added many times.

### Approach

* Pick every possible starting position of a subarray.
* Pick every possible ending position for that starting position.
* Compute the sum of all elements inside that subarray by scanning from start to end.
* Increase the answer whenever the computed sum equals the target.
* Return the total count after checking all subarrays.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
countSubarrays(arr, target) {

    /* Store the size of the array so all subarrays can be explored */
    n = arr.size()

    /* Track how many subarrays have sum equal to the target */
    count = 0

    /* Choose every possible starting index of a subarray */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Choose every possible ending index for the current start */
        for j = i to n - 1 {

            /* Reset the sum for the current subarray */
            sum = 0

            /* Add all elements from the current start to current end */
            for k = i to j {
                sum += arr[k]
            }

            /* If this subarray matches the required target, count it */
            if sum == target {
                count++
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the total number of valid subarrays found */
    return count
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int countSubarrays(vector<int>& arr, int target) {
        int n = arr.size();
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
                int sum = 0;
                for (int k = i; k <= j; k++) {
                    sum += arr[k];
                }
                if (sum == target) {
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
};

