### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity:** `O(n^3)`

  * We use three nested loops to generate every possible triplet, and each triplet is checked once.

* **Space Complexity:** `O(1)`

  * Only a few extra variables are used apart from the input array.


## Solution 

### Intuition

* Instead of fixing all three indices directly, this solution treats `j` as the middle index and `k` as the right index, then tries to count how many valid `i` indices can complete the triplet.

* For every pair `(j, k)`, we compute the remainder of `arr[j] + arr[k]` modulo `m`. To make the full triplet sum divisible by `m`, we need a previous value `arr[i]` whose remainder is exactly the missing remainder.

* The map `freq` stores how many earlier elements `arr[i]` have each remainder modulo `m`.

* So for each `(j, k)`, we directly add the count of matching earlier remainders from `freq`, which efficiently counts all valid triplets ending at `(j, k)`.

### Approach

* Traverse the array by fixing `j` as the middle index.

* For each `j`, try every `k > j` as the third index and compute the remainder of `arr[j] + arr[k]` modulo `m`.

* Find which remainder is needed from some earlier index `i` so that:

  * `(arr[i] + arr[j] + arr[k]) % m == 0`.

* Maintain a frequency map `freq` of remainders of all elements before `j`. This tells how many valid choices of `i` are available.

* For every pair `(j, k)`, add `freq[need]` to the answer.

* After finishing all `k` for the current `j`, insert the remainder of `arr[j]` into `freq` so it can be used for future triplets.

* Finally, return the total count of valid triplets.


### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
countTriplets(arr, m) {
    n = length of arr
    ans = 0
    /* freq stores how many earlier elements have each remainder modulo m */
    freq = empty map
    /* Fix j as the middle index */
    for (j = 0 to n - 1) {
        /* Try every k after j as the third index */
        for (k = j + 1 to n - 1) {
            /* Compute remainder of arr[j] + arr[k] */
            rem = (arr[j] + arr[k]) % m
            /* Find which remainder is needed from arr[i] */
            need = (m - rem) % m
            /* Add all valid earlier i choices */
            ans = ans + freq[need]
        }
        /* After finishing all k for this j, add arr[j] to frequency map */
        freq[arr[j] % m] = freq[arr[j] % m] + 1
    }
    return ans
}
```

</CodeBlock>


### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int countTriplets(vector<long long>& arr, int m) {
        int n = arr.size();
        long long ans = 0;
        unordered_map<int, int> freq;
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            for (int k = j + 1; k < n; k++) {
                int rem = (int)((1LL * arr[j] + arr[k]) % m);
                int need = (m - rem) % m;
                ans += freq[need];
            }
            freq[arr[j] % m]++;
        }
        return (int)ans;
    }
};

