# Fibonacci Array Transformation

## Solution

### Intuition

* Each array element must be replaced by the Fibonacci number of its own value.

* So the work has two recursive parts: one recursion computes the Fibonacci number for a single value, and another recursion moves through the array element by element.

* For the current index, we first compute the Fibonacci value of `arr[index]`, replace it, and then the same task remains for the rest of the array.

* Since the constraint on array values is small, the direct recursive Fibonacci approach is acceptable here.

### Approach

* Write a recursive function `fibonacci(x)` that returns the `x`-th Fibonacci number.

* Write another recursive function `transformArray(arr, n, index)` that processes one array position at a time.

* If `index == n`, stop because all elements are already transformed.

* Otherwise, replace `arr[index]` with `fibonacci(arr[index])` and recursively move to `index + 1`.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
fibonacci(x) {
    /* Base case for first two Fibonacci numbers */
    if (x == 0) {
        return 0
    }
    if (x == 1) {
        return 1
    }

    /* Recursive definition of Fibonacci */
    return fibonacci(x - 1) + fibonacci(x - 2)
}

transformArray(arr, n, index) {
    /* If all positions are processed, stop recursion */
    if (index == n) {
        return
    }

    /* Replace current value with its Fibonacci number */
    arr[index] = fibonacci(arr[index])

    /* Recursively process the next index */
    transformArray(arr, n, index + 1)
}

getTransformedArray(arr, n) {
    transformArray(arr, n, 0)
    return arr
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

