# Automorphic Number

## Solution 1

### Intuition

* An automorphic number is one whose square **ends with the same digits as the number itself**.
* So instead of comparing the whole number with its square, focus only on the **last digits**.
* Compare the last digit of the number and its square, then remove those last digits and repeat the same check.
* If every corresponding digit matches until the original number is exhausted, then the number is automorphic; if any digit differs, it is not.

### Approach

- Calculate the square of the given number.
- Compare the last digits of the number and its square till the number exists after removing its last digit in each iteration.
- If all digits match, return `true`; otherwise, return `false`.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vTG41l05vkkCKd2aPKV6-IaNKvqJiq-NE1vPW0i6Ftl9q-Rb1Xlb0GPNJp1VJ9IZ579EziR36H4ClXP/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudo Code


<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```
checkAutomorphicNumber(num) {
    /* Store the square of the given number */
    square = num * num

    /* Compare digits of num with the last digits of its square */
    while num > 0 {
        /* If the last digit of num and square do not match, then num is not an automorphic number */
        if num % 10 != square % 10 {
            return false
        }

        /* Remove the last digit from both num and square */
        num = num / 10
        square = square / 10
    }

    /* If all digits matched, then num is an automorphic number */
    return true
}
```

</CodeBlock>

