### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(m * n)`**

  * Counting neighbors for one cell checks at most 8 surrounding cells, so each cell is processed in constant time.
  * Scanning the full board visits all `m * n` cells once to compute the next state.
  * The dominant term is `O(m * n)` because the constant factor from checking 8 directions does not change the overall growth.

* **Space Complexity: `O(m * n)`**

  * A separate copy of the board is stored so updates do not affect future neighbor counts in the same generation.
  * Apart from that copy, only a few extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(m * n)`.

## Solution 2: In-Place State Encoding

### Intuition

* The extra copy is only needed because cells must be updated together, so we need a way to remember both the old state and the new state at the same time.
* This can be done by using temporary values inside the same grid to encode transitions between old and new states.
* It saves extra memory, but the state encoding is a little less direct to understand at first.

### Approach

* Use temporary values to represent cells that change state while still preserving whether they were originally live or dead.
* While scanning the grid, count live neighbors using only values that represent cells that were originally alive.
* Mark each cell with its temporary next-state value based on the four game rules.
* Make one more pass through the grid and convert all temporary values into final live or dead values.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
countNeighbors(board, r, c, m, n) {
    /* Start the live neighbor count from zero */
    neighbors = 0

    /* Check all cells around the current position */
    for i = r - 1 to r + 1 {

        /* Check all columns around the current position */
        for j = c - 1 to c + 1 {

            /* Skip the current cell and all out-of-bounds positions */
            if (i == r and j == c) or i < 0 or j < 0 or i >= m or j >= n {
                continue
            }

            /* Count only cells that were originally alive */
            if board[i][j] == 1 or board[i][j] == 3 {
                neighbors = neighbors + 1
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the total number of live neighbors */
    return neighbors
}

nextGenerationGrid(board) {
    /* Get the board dimensions */
    m = board.size()
    n = board[0].size()

    /* Visit every cell to assign temporary transition states */
    for r = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Process each column in the current row */
        for c = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* Count live neighbors using original live information */
            neighbors = countNeighbors(board, r, c, m, n)

            /* Keep a live cell alive when it has two or three neighbors */
            if board[r][c] == 1 {

                /* Mark a surviving live cell with a temporary value */
                if neighbors == 2 or neighbors == 3 {
                    board[r][c] = 3
                }
            }

            /* Revive a dead cell when it has exactly three neighbors */
            else {

                /* Mark a new live cell with a temporary value */
                if neighbors == 3 {
                    board[r][c] = 2
                }
            }
        }
    }

    /* Convert all temporary values into final board values */
    for r = 0 to m - 1 {

        /* Finalize each cell in the current row */
        for c = 0 to n - 1 {

            /* Cells left as one were originally live but must now die */
            if board[r][c] == 1 {
                board[r][c] = 0
            }

            /* Cells marked two or three must be alive in the next generation */
            else if board[r][c] == 2 or board[r][c] == 3 {
                board[r][c] = 1
            }
        }
    }

    /* The board now stores the next generation */
    return board
}
```

