### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n^2)`**

  * The recursion first moves inward until the first mismatch is found.
  * From that mismatch, we may try up to `O(n)` possible swap positions.
  * Each trial uses a recursive palindrome check that takes `O(n)`, so the total becomes `O(n^2)`.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The recursive calls use stack space.
  * The maximum recursion depth is linear in the length of the string.
  * So the extra space used is `O(n)`.

# Smallest Number

## Linear Scan for Minimum Element

### Intuition

* The smallest element is simply the value that is not greater than any other value in the array.
* A natural idea is to keep track of the smallest value seen so far while moving through the array once.
* This works because every new element is compared with the current smallest value, so by the end we are left with the true minimum.

### Approach

* Start by treating the first element as the smallest value.
* Move through the remaining elements one by one.
* Whenever a smaller value is found, update the current smallest value.
* After the full scan ends, return the stored smallest value.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
smallestElement(arr, n) {

    /* Start with the first element because it is the only known value initially */
    smallest = arr[0]

    /* Check every remaining element to see if a smaller value exists */
    for i = 1 to n - 1 {

        /* If the current element is smaller, update the answer */
        if arr[i] < smallest {

            /* Store this new smaller value as the current minimum */
            smallest = arr[i]
        }
    }

    /* After scanning the whole array, return the minimum value found */
    return smallest
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

