# Reverse A Number

## Solution

### Intuition

Reversing a number is similar to reading it from right to left.

* By repeatedly taking the last digit using modulo `10`, we can append it to a new number being built.

* Dividing the original number by `10` removes the processed digit.

* Doing this until the number becomes `0` constructs the reversed number.

### Approach

* Start with a variable to hold the reversed number.

* Extract the last digit of the number and add it to the reversed number.

* Remove the last digit from the original number and repeat.

* Return the reversed number after all digits are processed.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vSNUwgJm7rN_BNGd22WZUs5GTvhKc_BwX8ruHn8QNAUB_yYNlAtX2MM_Txwuc4oCcCbX3dHDk7OyK6e/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudo Code


<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">
```pseudocode
reverseNumber(N) {
    /* Variable to store the reversed number */
    reversed = 0

    /* Process digits until the number becomes 0 */
    while N != 0 {
        /* Extract the last digit of N */
        lastDigit = N mod 10

        /* Append this digit to the reversed number */
        reversed = reversed * 10 + lastDigit

        /* Remove the last digit from N */
        N = N / 10
    }

    /* Return the reversed number */
    return reversed
}

```
</CodeBlock>

