# Checking for Palindromic Numbers

## Solution

### Intuition

A number is a palindrome if it reads the same forward and backward.

So the idea is simple:

* Reverse the digits of the number.
* Then compare the reversed number with the original one.

If both are equal, the number looks the same from both directions — which means it is a palindrome.
If they differ, then the order of digits changes when reversed, so it is not a palindrome.

### Approach

* Keep a copy of the number before changing it.

* Reverse the digits by repeatedly taking the last digit and building a new number.

* Compare the reversed number with the original number.

* If both are equal, the number is a palindrome.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vTGUTOao3s4h--unIAao_P1NhpdoUz1tIXS-CoIbeJ7QjgNoy-xYpELnM5SFHmQ2FJ-eDEfESCYBIij/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudo Code


<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">
```pseudocode
isPalindrome(n) {
    /* Store the original number to compare later */
    original = n

    /* Variable to store the reversed number */
    reversed = 0

    /* Reverse the digits of the number */
    while n != 0 {
        /* Extract the last digit */
        lastDigit = n mod 10

        /* Append the last digit to the reversed number */
        reversed = reversed * 10 + lastDigit

        /* Remove the last digit from n */
        n = n / 10
    }

    /* If reversed number equals original, it is a palindrome */
    return reversed == original
}
```
</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

