# Checking for Prime Numbers

## Solution

### Intuition

A prime number has exactly two divisors: `1` and itself.

Instead of checking all numbers from `1` to `n`, we can optimize:

* If a number has a divisor greater than `√n`, it must also have a corresponding divisor smaller than `√n`.

* So, we only need to check divisibility up to `√n`.

* If we find any divisor (other than `1` and `n`), the number is not prime.

This makes the solution much more efficient than checking all numbers up to `n`.

### Approach

* First handle small numbers, since values less than or equal to one are not prime.

* Check all possible divisors only up to the square root of the number.

* Count how many times the number is perfectly divisible.

* If exactly two divisors exist, the number is prime; otherwise, it is not.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
