# Sum of Divisors

## Solution

### Intuition

Divisors of a number always come in pairs.

If `i` divides `num`, then `num / i` is also a divisor.

For example, for `16`:

* `2` is a divisor → `16 / 2 = 8` is also a divisor.

So instead of checking all numbers up to `num`, we only check up to `√num`.

* For every divisor found before `√num`, we automatically get its pair.

* If the number is a perfect square (like `16`), the square root is added only once.

### Approach

- Iterate through numbers up to the square root of the given number.

- For each divisor, add both the divisor and its corresponding quotient to the sum.

- If the divisor equals the square root, add it only once to avoid duplication.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vQ5Xn-ABH98ora84uy51k8ie3yQzs5o1seFM8cP0gxJCVDRxVzLEPxJikZr2AXlmoOb8Qbl5a6V41tL/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudo Code


<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```
sumOfDivisors(num) {
    sum = 0
    for i from 1 to sqrt(num) {     /* After the square root of the number, divisors start repeating */
        if (num % i == 0) {
            if (num / i == i) sum += i  /* If the number is square root, add only once to the sum */
            else sum += (i + num / i)   /* If i is a divisor, then num/i is also a divisor */
        }
    }
    return sum
}
```

</CodeBlock>

