# Largest Subarray Sum

## Solution 1: Brute Force Solution

### Intuition

* The most direct idea is to generate every possible subarray and calculate its sum.
* Since every subarray is checked, the largest sum will definitely be found.
* This method is easy to understand, but it becomes very slow because the same elements are added again and again.

### Approach

* Choose each position as the starting point of a subarray.
* For every starting point, choose each possible ending point after it.
* For each chosen range, add all elements inside that range to get its sum.
* Keep track of the largest sum seen during the whole process.
* Return the largest sum at the end.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
largestSubarraySum(arr) {
    /* Store the size of the array and initialize the final answer */
    n = arr.size()
    ans = -∞

    /* Try every possible starting index */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Try every possible ending index for the current start */
        for j = i to n - 1 {
            sum = 0

            /* Compute the sum of the current subarray */
            for k = i to j {
                sum = sum + arr[k]
            }

            /* Update the maximum subarray sum */
            ans = max(ans, sum)
        }
    }

    /* Return the largest subarray sum found */
    return ans
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int largestSubarraySum(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        int ans = INT_MIN;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
                int sum = 0;
                for (int k = i; k <= j; k++) {
                    sum += arr[k];
                }
                ans = max(ans, sum);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

