### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n^3)`**

  * The first loop chooses the starting position of the subarray, and the second loop chooses the ending position.
  * For every chosen range, the third loop adds all elements inside that subarray, which can take linear time.
  * The dominant term is `O(n^3)` because three nested loops are used.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * Only a few variables are used to store the current sum, answer, and loop positions.
  * Only constant extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

## Solution 2: Better Solution

### Intuition

* In the previous method, the same subarray sums are built from scratch many times.
* We can do better by fixing a starting point and extending the subarray one element at a time.
* This avoids the extra inner summing loop, so the solution becomes faster while still checking all subarrays.

### Approach

* Choose each position as the starting point of a subarray.
* Start with a sum of zero for that starting point.
* Extend the subarray one position at a time toward the right and keep adding the new element to the current sum.
* After every extension, compare the current sum with the best answer seen so far.
* Return the largest sum at the end.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
largestSubarraySum(arr) {
    /* Store the size of the array and initialize the final answer */
    n = arr.size()
    ans = -∞

    /* Fix each starting index one by one */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {
        sum = 0

        /* Extend the subarray from the current start */
        for j = i to n - 1 {
            sum = sum + arr[j]

            /* Update the maximum subarray sum */
            ans = max(ans, sum)
        }
    }

    /* Return the largest subarray sum found */
    return ans
}
```

</CodeBlock>

