### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The array is scanned only once from left to right.
  * Every step does constant work: one addition, one comparison, and at most one reset.
  * The dominant term is `O(n)` because each element is processed once.

* **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  * Only the running sum and the best answer are stored apart from the input array.
  * Only constant extra variables are used, costing `O(1)`.
  * Total space used is `O(1)`.

# Max Pair Sum in Subarrays

## Solution 1: Enumerate All Subarrays and Track Two Minimums

### Intuition

* A direct way to solve this is to try every possible subarray and compute its value separately.
* For each chosen subarray, we only need its two smallest elements because their sum defines the answer for that subarray.
* This idea is easy to trust because it checks every valid choice, but it becomes slow since the same elements are scanned many times.

### Approach

* Consider every possible subarray with length at least two.
* For each subarray, scan all of its elements and keep track of the smallest and second smallest values.
* Compute the sum of those two values for the current subarray.
* Keep updating the best answer seen across all subarrays.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
maxPairSum(arr, n) {
    /* Return failure when the array does not contain a valid subarray */
    if n < 2 {
        return -1
    }

    /* Start with a very small answer so any real sum can replace it */
    maxSum = -infinity

    /* Pick every possible starting position of a subarray */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* Pick every possible ending position after the start */
        for j = i + 1 to n - 1 {

            /* Reset the two minimum values for the current subarray */
            min1 = infinity
            min2 = infinity

            /* Scan the current subarray to find its two smallest elements */
            for k = i to j {

                /* Update both minimum values when a new smallest element appears */
                if arr[k] < min1 {
                    min2 = min1
                    min1 = arr[k]
                }

                /* Otherwise update only the second smallest value when needed */
                else if arr[k] < min2 {
                    min2 = arr[k]
                }
            }

            /* Use this subarray only when two valid minimum values exist */
            if min2 != infinity {

                /* Keep the maximum value found among all subarrays */
                maxSum = max(maxSum, min1 + min2)
            }
        }
    }

    /* Return the best value found */
    return maxSum
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int maxPairSum(vector<int>& arr, int n) {
        if (n < 2) {
            return -1;
        }

        int maxSum = INT_MIN;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                int min1 = INT_MAX, min2 = INT_MAX;

                for (int k = i; k <= j; k++) {
                    if (arr[k] < min1) {
                        min2 = min1;
                        min1 = arr[k];
                    } else if (arr[k] < min2) {
                        min2 = arr[k];
                    }
                }

                if (min2 != INT_MAX) {
                    maxSum = max(maxSum, min1 + min2);
                }
            }
        }

        return maxSum;
    }
};

