### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity : `O(3^n)`**

  * For each call to `tribonacci(n)`, the function makes three recursive calls: `tribonacci(n-1)`, `tribonacci(n-2)`, and `tribonacci(n-3)`.

  * Many subproblems are solved repeatedly, which causes the number of calls to grow exponentially with `n`.

  * Therefore, the overall time complexity is exponential, approximately `O(3^n)`.

* **Space Complexity : `O(n)`**

  * The space is used by the recursive call stack.

  * In the worst case, the recursion depth can go up to `n`, so the space complexity is `O(n)`.

# Generalized Fibonacci Sequence

## Solution

### Intuition

* The sequence already starts with the first `k` values, so we only need to keep generating the remaining numbers.

* Every new number depends only on the last `k` numbers currently present in the sequence.

* So after computing that sum once, the same task remains for a sequence that is now one element longer.

* This makes recursion natural because each call adds one valid next term and reduces the remaining work.

### Approach

* If `n` is less than or equal to `k`, return only the first `n` elements from the starting array.

* Otherwise, use recursion until the sequence size becomes exactly `n`.

* In each recursive call, compute the sum of the last `k` elements of the current sequence.

* Append that sum to the sequence and recursively generate the next term.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
generateGeneralizedFibonacci(k, start, n) {
    /* If only first n values are needed, return that prefix */
    if (n <= length of start) {
        return first n elements of start
    }

    /* If sequence already reached required size, stop recursion */
    if (length of start == n) {
        return start
    }

    /* Compute the next value using the last k numbers */
    nextNumber = 0
    for (i = length of start - k to length of start - 1) {
        nextNumber = nextNumber + start[i]
    }

    /* Add the new number and continue recursively */
    start.push_back(nextNumber)

    return generateGeneralizedFibonacci(k, start, n)
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    vector<int> generateGeneralizedFibonacci(int k, vector<int>& start, int n) {
        if (n <= (int)start.size()) {
            return vector<int>(start.begin(), start.begin() + n);
        }

        if ((int)start.size() == n) {
            return start;
        }

        int nextNumber = 0;
        for (int i = (int)start.size() - k; i < (int)start.size(); i++) {
            nextNumber += start[i];
        }

        start.push_back(nextNumber);

        return generateGeneralizedFibonacci(k, start, n);
    }
};

