### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity: `O((n - k) * k)`**

  * For each newly generated term, the algorithm sums the last `k` numbers.
  * This happens for `n - k` recursive extensions when `n > k`.
  * So the total running time is `O((n - k) * k)`.

* **Space Complexity: `O(n)`**

  * The final sequence stores up to `n` numbers.
  * The recursion depth can go up to `n - k` in the worst case.
  * So the total extra space is `O(n)`.

# Search Element in Rotated Sorted Array

## Solution

### Intuition

Even though the array looks “broken” because of rotation, one important thing is still true: at any middle point, at least one half (left or right) will still be sorted.

So instead of searching linearly, we use the middle element like normal binary search, but with one extra thought:

* First, figure out which half is properly sorted (because only one pivot exists).

* Then ask: does `k` belong to that sorted half’s range?

  * If yes, the answer must be inside that half → we continue searching there.

  * If no, the answer must be in the other half → we discard the sorted half.

### Approach

* Use binary search, but first check which half of the array is already sorted.

* If the target lies inside that sorted half, search only there.

* Otherwise, search in the other half.

* Keep narrowing the range until the target is found or the range becomes empty.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vSU0fxR3hfJbm9pRQpLx5wljz-MAkKjhjqHcgZ5cchHVFmUUNT2p31wMaWdpmjESZovSFuVOohpo4Gv/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">
```pseudocode
searchRotatedSorted(arr, n, x){
    low = 0
    high = n - 1

    /* Binary search on a rotated sorted array */
    while low <= high {

        mid = (low + high) / 2

        /* If mid element is the target, return it */
        if arr[mid] == x {
            return mid
        }

        /* Check if the left half [low..mid] is sorted */
        else if arr[low] <= arr[mid] {

            /* If x lies in the sorted left half, discard right half */
            if arr[low] <= x AND x <= arr[mid] {
                high = mid - 1
            }
            /* Otherwise, discard left half */
            else {
                low = mid + 1
            }
        }

        /* Otherwise, the right half [mid..high] is sorted */
        else {

            /* If x lies in the sorted right half, discard left half */
            if arr[mid] <= x AND x <= arr[high] {
                low = mid + 1
            }
            /* Otherwise, discard right half */
            else {
                high = mid - 1
            }
        }
    }

    /* Target not found */
    return -1
}
```
</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int searchRotatedSorted(int arr[], int n, int x){
        int low=0,high=n-1;
        while(low<=high){
            int mid = (low+high)/2;
            if(arr[mid]==x){
                return mid;
            }
            else if(arr[low]<=arr[mid]){
                if(arr[low]<=x && x<=arr[mid]){
                    high=mid-1;
                }
                else{
                    low=mid+1;
                }
            }
            else if(arr[mid]<=arr[high]){
                if(arr[mid]<=x && x<=arr[high]){
                    low=mid+1;
                }
                else{
                    high=mid-1;
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};

