# Remove Duplicates II

## Solution: Counting Consecutive Occurrences

### Intuition

* Since the array is already sorted, all duplicates appear next to each other.
* That means we can process the array from left to right and count how many times the current value has appeared in a row.
* We keep writing elements back into the same array, but only while their count does not go above two.

### Approach

* Handle the empty array case first.
* Keep one position to place the next valid element in the array.
* Move through the array from left to right and count consecutive equal values.
* Reset the count when a new value appears.
* Copy the current element only when its count is at most two.
* Return the final write position as the new length.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```pseudocode
removeDup(arr) {
    /* Handle the empty array case */
    if arr.size() == 0 {
        return 0
    }

    /* Initialize the write position and count */
    i = 1
    count = 1

    /* Traverse the array from left to right */
    for j = 1 to arr.size() - 1 {

        /* Update the count of the current value */
        if arr[j] == arr[j - 1] {
            count = count + 1
        }
        else {
            count = 1
        }

        /* Keep the element only if it appears at most twice */
        if count <= 2 {
            arr[i] = arr[j]
            i = i + 1
        }
    }

    /* Return the new valid length */
    return i
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    int removeDup(vector<int>& arr) {
        if (arr.empty()) {
            return 0;
        }

        int i = 1;
        int count = 1;

        for (int j = 1; j < arr.size(); j++) {
            if (arr[j] == arr[j - 1]) {
                count++;
            } else {
                count = 1;
            }

            if (count <= 2) {
                arr[i] = arr[j];
                i++;
            }
        }

        return i;
    }
};

