# Missing number

## Solution 1 : Sorting 

### Intuition

* Think of the numbers as forming a perfect sequence from `0` to `n`. If one number is missing, there will be a “gap” in this sequence.
* Sorting the array first lines up the numbers in order, making gaps easy to spot.
* After sorting, check the first and last elements—if the missing number is at the boundaries, it’s immediately obvious.
* Otherwise, iterate through the sorted array and look for a mismatch between the current number and the number you expect (`previous + 1`). The first mismatch reveals the missing number.

### Approach

* Begin by sorting the input array `arr` to arrange the elements in ascending order. This helps in ensuring that the elements are in a sequential order.
* Check the boundary conditions by first verifying if the first and last elements are `0` and `n` respectively. If not, then one of them is the missing number.
* Iterate through the sorted array from the second element to the last. For each element, calculate the expected value as the previous element plus one. If the current element does not match this expected value, return the expected value as the missing number.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vRnYX7_9hRsKFP4Xio-ibJEy-iIn_uxApOhSBBeGjCs3lrvlJYEy00VzlGRQNUcBCXqiTosWhhfDoZJ/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudo Code


<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
missingNumber(arr) {
    /* Get the size of the array */
    n = size of arr
    /* Sort the array in ascending order */
    sort(arr)
    /* Check if the last element is not equal to n. If so, n is the missing number. */
    if arr[n - 1] != n {
        return n
    }
    /* Check if the first element is not 0. If so, 0 is the missing number. */
    else if arr[0] != 0 {
        return 0
    }
    /* Traverse the array to find the first gap between consecutive numbers */
    for i = 1 to n - 1 {
        /* Expected number after previous element */
        num = arr[i - 1] + 1
        /* If current element is not equal to expected, it's the missing number */
        if arr[i] != num {
            return num
        }
    }
    /* Edge case: if no missing number found, return -1 */
    return -1
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution{
public:
    int missingNumber(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());

        if(arr[n-1] != n) return n;
        else if(arr[0] != 0) return 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            int num = arr[i-1] + 1;
            if (arr[i] != num) {
                return num;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};

