## Solution 2 : Hash Map

### Intuition

* Instead of rearranging numbers, focus on tracking what exists and what doesn’t.
* Use a map as a quick lookup tool — it helps remember which numbers have appeared.
* Once all elements are recorded, imagine checking the complete range from `0` to `n`.
* The missing number is simply the one that was never stored in the map.
* This method converts the problem into a presence-checking task rather than an ordering task.

### Approach

* Count how many times each number appears using a map.
* Scan all numbers from the full expected range.
* The number that never appeared is the missing one.
* Return that number immediately.

### Dry Run

<div style="position: relative; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 59.27%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
  <iframe 
    src="https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vQBXBNbpjSivrRKp41D1JRRt1HegamAW_52lpyaNa675SDgozXrhyNq6jBxE3zP8yA7fk17r1hdLsig/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000" 
    style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0;" 
    allowfullscreen="true" 
    mozallowfullscreen="true" 
    webkitallowfullscreen="true">
  </iframe>
</div>

### Pseudo Code


<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```
missingNumber(arr) {
    /* Find the missing number in range 0 to n */
    n = arr.size()
    /* Create a hash map to store frequency of elements */
    m = empty unordered_map
    /* Store occurrences of each element in the map */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {
        m[arr[i]] = m[arr[i]] + 1
    }
    /* Check every number from 0 to n */
    for i = 0 to n {
        /* If i is not present in the map, it is missing */
        if m.find(i) == m.end() {
            return i
        }
    }
    /* Default return (will not normally reach here) */
    return 0
}

```

</CodeBlock>


### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution{
public:
    int missingNumber(vector<int> &arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        unordered_map<int, int> m;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            m[arr[i]]++;
        }

        for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
            if(m.find(i) == m.end()) {
                return i;
            }
        }
        return 0;
    }
};

