### Complexity Analysis

- **Time Complexity: `O(n)`**

  - One loop iterates through the array: `O(n)`.

  - Total: `O(n)`, where `n` is the size of the array `arr`.

- **Space Complexity: `O(1)`**

  - Uses constant space for variables `result` and loop index.

# Second Smallest Element

## Solution

### Intuition

* We only care about the smallest and the second smallest values, so storing the full sorted order is unnecessary.
* While scanning the array once, we can keep updating these two answers whenever a smaller value appears.
* This works because every element can only affect one of these two tracked values, making the method both fast and space efficient.

### Approach

* Start with two very large values to represent the current smallest and second smallest elements.
* Traverse the array once from left to right.
* If the current element is smaller than the smallest value, move the old smallest value to second smallest.
* Otherwise, if it is smaller than second smallest, update second smallest.
* Return the second smallest value after the full scan ends.

### Pseudocode

<CodeBlock language="text" showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle="normal">

```plaintext
secondSmallestElement(arr, n) {
    /* Initialize both answers with very large values so real elements can replace them */
    smallest = 1000000000
    secondSmallest = 1000000000

    /* Traverse the array once to maintain the two minimum values */
    for i = 0 to n - 1 {

        /* If the current element is the new smallest, shift the old smallest to second smallest */
        if arr[i] < smallest {

            /* Preserve the previous smallest as the second smallest candidate */
            secondSmallest = smallest

            /* Update the smallest value */
            smallest = arr[i]
        }

        /* Otherwise, check whether the current element belongs in the second smallest position */
        else if arr[i] < secondSmallest {

            /* Update the second smallest value */
            secondSmallest = arr[i]
        }
    }

    /* Return the second smallest value after the scan */
    return secondSmallest
}
```

</CodeBlock>

### Code Implementation

<MultiLanguageCodeBlock enableMoveCode={true}>

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution{
public:
    int secondSmallestElement(int arr[], int n){
        int smallest = INT_MAX;
        int secondSmallest = INT_MAX;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (arr[i] < smallest) {
                secondSmallest = smallest;
                smallest = arr[i];
            } else if (arr[i] > smallest && arr[i] < secondSmallest) {
                secondSmallest = arr[i];
            }
        }

        return secondSmallest == INT_MAX ? -1 : secondSmallest;
    }
};

